text: I have a personal theory that the thing most responsible for Dr. Hawking being alive today,more than anything else in his post diagnosis world, save for the exception of his wife, is that little computer. Not in any measurable way. It doesn't regulate any body part I'm aware of, except one. His mind! By giving him the ability to allow his ideas to escape.  Ask any creator or artist and they will tell you that the most distressing part of creating, is not being able to express the ideas that take hold of your mind and demand to be released into the world. The all consuming compulsion to have life charged into your thoughts by making them tangible in some way. Trust me Theoretical Physics and Mathematics take just as much creativity and abstract thinking as any song or painting. Look at the concept Einstein's theory of Special Relativity (E=MC¬≤) presents, with such beauty and elegance, then tell me honestly you don't see art in it.  If Dr. Hawking was to be, not only bed ridden, immobilized, but silenced by his disease as well, I would imagine his life would have ended much earlier. Instead of the 100 years from now, where he will pass away as the result of being shot by the jealous husband of a 22 year old centerfold model. Like Dr. Hawking can help how sexy women find his big... brain!  Seriously though. I don't mean just his ability to describe a problem to those who assist him with his health. That may obviously be the difference in life and death, but that of his personal worth, gained from the mono-tone American accent of his computer.  I imagine this man is so full of thought and reasoning that his mind is even defying death itself. It is like his physical life is more horrifying than an H.R.Giger painting but still, he treks on. Not only because of his love for his wonderful and saintly wife but because he has purpose and with purpose comes drive. With drive you gain resolve and with resolve, life. He is here not just for himself and his loved ones but for us. Believing that this world is the only chance you get at existence. That with that belief, the closest you get to immortality is being remembered by the world for you deeds. I think his memory will always be that of a teacher. Just think of all the profound ways in which he teaches us. Not just in his field of study but in his life. All while never saying a word with his own breath. I admire, respect, and adore Hawking on each and every level we usually judge one another.

text: I don't understand why it's so incredibly hard for Hollywood to ACTUALLY make biopics about the discoveries, hardships, and struggles these scientists, engineers, doctors and businessmen faced when dealing with some sort of underlying scientific foundation. These scripts do not need to be spoon-fed or dumbed down for audiences, It needs to stick with a centralized and focused point about the person in question. This for example could've talked greatly about how Hawking came about with his theories regarding black holes and delve into such topics as Hawking Radiation, Black Hole Entropy, The Singularity or even the Information Loss Paradox which by the could tie nicely in with Hawking's feud with another famous physicist Leonard Susskind. But no, they've decided to make another "Hollywood" story that focuses more on Hawking's relationship with his wife Jane and how they both cope with his ALS probably for the sake of another emotional baggage love story.¬†  Primer is a great example of what I'm talking ¬†about. AND Shane Carruth, director and actor in the movie, actually has a background in software engineering and mathematics, so the way he presents his story is reflected through his script's technical dialogue which added a layer of depth to his story, which I personally loved.  If this is how keeps going with Jobs and now this, I'm just keen on the day they decide to make a biopic about Newton, Einstein, Darwin, Tesla, Bohr, Planck, Fleming, or even the great David Hilbert and have it NOT have to do ANYTHING with their personal struggle to find exactly what they wanted from their lifetime and what they wanted to achieve, and instead focus some other innocuous aspect about their life which deters so much away from what they actually accomplished that it almost gives the audience an entirely wrong perspective of the person they truly are and/or what the difficulties and struggles they went through to become some of the most well respected, most influential people in human history.  Fuck you Hollywood. I'm done.¬†  Note: Despite all that I have said, this does look like a fairly well crafted movie, and I will probably go see it with my friends when it comes out.¬†

text: Makes me think of Baudrillard's simulacrum and the difference that one's simulacrum is from the historical person. While it's impossible to make a completely objective and accurate biopic of anyone, it seems kind of weird that the role of marital love is so heavily emphasized as an enabler for him in this movie considering the fact that he left Elaine for his nurse, divorced the nurse, and has now been single for 8 years. In fact, Elaine has commented about how her influence in his life was specifically removed by the presence of nurses and assistants. She says her primary role was to remind him that he wasn't god. So it's kind of using Hawking to tell a morality tale about love that didn't actually work out in reality.

text: Divorce, misrepresenting moniker of a title, presumably a drama enthralled cliche fest emphasizing upon ironic romantic interactions between Hawking and his first wife rather than the brilliant cosmological research Hawking managed whilst treating his illness: All logically valid reasons why this film will be redundantly irrelevant. Another regurgitated, exaggerated, misinterpreted Hollywood-like mockery of a film, which will--probably--excel monetarily. Of course, all of this is speculation. Who knows, it may actually well be a decent film that encapsulates the essence, the persona of Stephen Hawking. Not as one of the greatest minds of a generation that has been woefully stricken by a--literally--crippling disease (Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis), but rather, more of a romantic ladies man with a thing for black holes. bwahahahhahahahahahahaha. I'm sorry I couldn't type that with a straight face. Shame really, Hawking's life is quite interesting. Could've been a proper film, if only they'd have stuck to the importance of his work and sidelined his personal affairs. Then again, what am I saying. As if 99% of the planet's general populace have even the slightest notion pertaining to Hawking's extraordinary insights in the fields of General Relativity and Cosmology. In fact, just by browsing through a few of the comments some individuals have made, it is apparent that a vast amount of people are psychologically stuck in the dark ages.

text: How is Hawking and his Ex-wife okay with their relationship being shown to the whole world? I would understand if one had passed away whilst they where married or something but they got a divorce and apparently a messy one.¬†A major part of their relationship breaking down was due to publicity and fame. They have both been associated with different people during and after their marriage. Also Hawking has even had a second wife (I know about the abuse allegations, but I don't know enough to give any opinion on it). Also I love all the actors in this film, but it does look like a exact scene to scene reenactment of BBC Hawking for the start of the movie. And I can bet it will probably end with the cliched it all seeming very happy and so forth but then there will be the usual black screen with the basic small font quickly telling you 'the love story you just witnessed doesn't have a happy ending but we are going make it look that way so that more people will be interested and people who don't know anything about Hawking or didn't take there glasses don't read this message and we all carry on being stupid as hell because you believe anything you see on a screen.' If this film actually shows what really happened, that yes, they where very happy to begin with but as time progressed they where drawn apart and the pressure and fame became too much of a strain on their marriage that they had to split up, and only with years of distance and separation where they able to come together to begin to mend and heal their relationship, I will be very, very shocked and surprised.¬†

text: Stephen Hawking asked what would happen if he could somehow reverse time back to when time first began. I think it is hilarious that some people actually believe that if that happened, we would see¬†a humanoid, bearded, robed, magical patriarch who would create mankind just so they would worship him or be tortured forever. Use your minds people. There is no evidence that supports this "god" hypothesis, yet people everywhere believe it. I'm not saying that is a bad thing, as people should have the right to believe what they want. I just wish people would expel these beliefs and look at them as what they truly are, myths. Myths created by man to explain what we do not know. Millions of years ago, people looked to the sky and wondered where rain came from, so they figured it must have been the rain god. No, we can now explain where precipitation comes from, and it is not god. The sad thing is, if people would see these works of fiction for what they really are (Bible, Quran, etc.), we could spend more time enjoying some of the stories/messages rather than examining the disgusting, twisted stories.

text: First of all it says so in the title The "theory" of everything. All Mr hawking has done is dedicate his life to nothing more than theories. Has any one of those theories ever been proven through actual application? NO. Do you understand why? Because it takes theorems and complicated mathematics based on things they only think they can understand. Just because Darwin sailed to an island in the 1800's and observed some finches with no actual scientific proof does not mean evolution exists. Just because an apple fell on Issac newtons head doesn't mean that gravity exists. Just because someone came up with an idea and everyone at the time accepted it and perpetuated the lie does not mean its true. Given a long enough span of time you can say anything about history and people will accept it. Look at Atlantis, its a fictional place mentioned once in a paragraph hundreds of years ago as an allegory for the brazen ineptitude of the ruling empires at the time and how they would eventually fall under their own hubris. Yet we still have television programs and "educated" scholars believing it exists and stupidly spending money on expeditions. THE BIBLE has been proven beyond any shadow of any doubt to have happened and to have existed. Everything, from prophecy to person to place to thing can be substantiated. I dont need theories or as I call them LIES to tell me about the world. The bible goes over everything. From society,law,ethics,money ect. We would be much more advanced as a society in our complete knowledge if we just followed one book and its not a breif history of time. The bible tells you about the past,present and yes even THE FUTURE. I strongly encourage you to try and poke holes in it.

text: So I think there are many commenters here who confuse the notion of true love with eternal connection. Just because a relationship doesn't last until death doesn't mean that for the time that¬†a couple was together, it¬†wasn't true love. Circumstances change all the time that make people fall in and out¬†of love. This would be analogous to saying that after 20 years of driving a reliable and dependable car that never broke down, the second it breaks down it was never a good car for the entire time you drove it. No, it was a well-functioning car until it wasn't, just like how love is love until is ceases being love.¬†You're¬†lying to yourself if you throw out the good times with the inevitable bad¬†ones. ¬†

I have been the victim of profound discrimination on these forums simply because I choose to think for myself and reject the plebeian notion of a "high power". text: Judging from the comments in this section, it would seem as though over 85% of the populous is still psychologically stuck in a primitive caveman - like state. Furthermore, this movie is a sad attempt to appeal to the majority of all the "feelers" out there, completely neglecting the works of Stephen Hawking, and the main theme of his life: Persistence. He managed to overcome one of the deadliest motor neuron diseases known to man, and come out on top of the heap with some of the greatest theories of all time. Yet this movie chooses to instead focus on some petty love story, meant only to appeal to the most emotional audiences. This is Hollywood bullshit at its prime. Maybe someday people will come to realize how much they've ignored and warped true life stories into their own sad entertainment.  That is all.

text: Without pain (and/or suffering) we as humans would never be able to appreciate the pleasures of life--- nor be able to discern what is good, bad, evil, truth, etc. If one really thinks about this, one would realize that life cannot exist--- free will cannot exist--- knowledge and wisdom cannot exist--- without there being two extremes, polar opposites. When people experience pain/suffering, they learn from such experiences. Either it can strengthen you, or it can destroy you. People say "If God exists, why is there evil and suffering?", and I would point out that without suffering, people in and of themselves could never grow/adapt and become better people--- or have the want, need, desire, to want to go and change the world for the better.  Trust me, alot of the time I cannot fathom or understand the thoughts of God, and really none of us ever will completely--- "Mysteries I will reveal to you, secret I will keep," (Job) but if one searches their hearts and minds--- and reflects on life and experiences--- the answer to suffering/evil is and always was there right in front of us. "What doesn't kill us, makes us stronger." These things are allowed/permissable so that we as people can endeavor and to not only survive, but to thrive.  Jesus bless.

text: The Theory of Everything‚Äôs marketing materials will tell you it is based on Jane Hawking‚Äôs memoir of her marriage, a book published in the UK as Music to Move the Stars and then reissued as Travelling to Infinity. But the screenwriter‚Äôs gone and rearranged the facts to suit certain dramatic conventions. And while that always happens in these based-on-a-true-story films, the scale of the departure in The Theory of Everything is unusually wide. The film becomes almost dishonest ‚Äì in a way that feels unfair to both parties, and oddly, particularly Jane Hawking herself

text: It is a strange feeling, but no matter what Professor Stephen Hawking has stated in the past--anti Semitic or anti Christian words--I still feel partial to his studies. Even knowing some consider his findings obscure or hard to follow, I have always been a Christian and have appreciated many of Professor Stephen Hawking's findings. Naturally I disagree with some of Stephen's theories, but he has made many leaps in science that I enjoy reading about.  I feel compelled to see this movie and I have always wished that I could do something in Professor Stephen Hawking's field to help heal him. More than anything, he has taken a lot of emotional and spiritual hits from life. I can see why he doesn't believe in God--but I hope he finds happiness in his life. I wish I could heal him of his past dismal experiences.¬†

text: A real fan of science should check out "The Theory of Everything", a movie about theoretical physicist Stephen Hawking who mathematically proved space-time singularity (i.e., black hole), instead of popular movie "Interstellar" that should be categorized as a space-fantasy movie like Star Wars or Thor. Nevertheless, adapted from the memoir of his first wife, this movie is more about his private life and Lou Gehrig's disease than academia or theoretical physics. It plays like a well-produced TV movie, though now we get to see how he acquired his robotic voice and ability to type 4 words a minute (imagine writing a physics book at that speed while his mind is still moving at lightspeed). The title itself is ironic since he is no longer pursuing the Theory of Everything that binds quantum mechanics and general relativity, according to his latest book "Grand Design". Then again, the movie stops at the book tour of his first popular book (actually most unread best seller of all time), "A Brief History of Time". I would recommend renting this movie right before the Oscar season. You know any actor who plays a seriously handicapped person becomes a strong contender for the best actor award.

With every theory that has come along in physics you've had nay sayers and critics. Facts disproven and rethought or evolved upon. But, this movie, knowing going in that it would effect me a great deal, took me beyond expectations. It was beautiful. Go see it, you'll be doing yourself a favor. Mr. and Mrs. Hawking are inspiration personified. And these actors did a bloody brilliant job portraying their world. Hate all you want. text: My proof against creationism:  Regardless of when our universe began, regardless of whether or not there were multiple universes before ours, or even whether or not there are multiple universes contemporarily coexisting with ours, and regardless of if and when time itself ever began, there had to have been some point in time when life or even intelligent life never existed...anywhere. Hypothetically, let's imagine this particular point in time, anywhere in the universe/multiverse/etc. If no intelligent life is currently existing, then intelligence itself cannot exist, and therefore an intelligent creator cannot exist. Given that certain objects such as galaxies, stars, and particularly planets/moons must exist before life itself can form and subsequently evolve into some form of intelligence, then it must also be true that an intelligent creator could not yet have been present to create the universe and objects within it such as galaxies, stars, planets/moons, etc. Therefore, the universe itself (or multiverse) and anything within it which existed before the existence of life, could not have been created by a god, AND, life itself could not have been created by a god since life must first evolve before becoming intelligent. Unless, of course, there is some way for intelligence to exist without anything having first existed, or unless there there is some way for intelligence to exist spontaneously without any form of life having first existed.  But let's be honest with ourselves here, does that really sound plausible? I mean REALLY think about it, and think about how the idea of a creator even came into existence during man's early history. Do you REALLY think it's that likely? Anyhow, I am not saying definitively whether or not an intelligent creator exists; I am simply using logic to imply that such a creator would be extremely unlikely.¬†  Now, please do not leave hateful comments; let us not blur our thoughts with negative emotions. If you would like to refute this, or offer proofs/ideas/suggestions which you think are capable of deconstructing my logic, then I would be more than happy to hear them and engage in some intellectual debate in a gentlemanly manner. But please don't be a dick...¬†

text: My mother is a fairly fundamentalist Christian, and I grew out of it at about 18 years of age. Just a little background. ¬† I told my mother about this movie, and how it told Hawking's story of love and tragedy, and overcoming the odds and a literal death sentence to go on to help the world despite his debilitation. I mentioned that maybe we could watch it as a family, since we don't do that very often... And she just said, "Well... He's a pretty outspoken *atheist*..." And that was that.¬† ¬† It really opened my eyes to see how even the most loving, caring people you know can be corrupted by religion. I know my mother is an amazing, loving person who raised me the right way and does all she can for me, but just saying the word "atheist" made her cringe as if she smelled something disgusting and vile. How can she see a story as touching and inspiring as this, and just totally ignore its beauty because Hawking thinks differently than she does? Well, religion is just about the only way that could happen, and it's made me dislike religion as a whole even more. Stupid intolerance and willful ignorance have ruined so much for society, and it pisses me off that it still goes on in the TWENTY-FIRST CENTURY. Just enjoy a fucking love story without bringing your hateful religious bullshit into it.¬† ¬† Well, I'm glad I got that out lol.

text: "There should be no boundaries to human endeavor. We are all different. However bad life may seem, there is always something you can do and succeed at. While there‚Äôs life, there is hope." - Stephen Hawking  Just finish watching this enormously inspirational film. It touched my heart and watered my eyes during multiple scenes. I believe that anybody, like myself, after watching this film will admire Dr. Stephen Hawking by the bottom of your heart. However, more than Hawking, my utmost respect goes to the woman that stood behind him for 30 years, gave birth to his 3 children, and greatly sacrificed the most beautiful years of her life for his massive success.¬†  I have a cousin who was born with impaired hearing, speaking, and mobility. He has the sweetest and most benevolent soul that I have ever known in my life. However, he often feels hopeless and down and that life is not fair to him even though his condition is much better and more fortunate than Hawking's. I want to share this film with him and everybody else who wants to give up on something. If Stephen Hawking can overcome what life throws at him and succeeds what he has done for the humanity, YOU can overcome your whatever obstacles. Yes, YOU can do that!¬†  And don‚Äôt you ever feel that life is not fair! This reminds me of a saying from my old folks, ‚ÄúThe Creator is very fair. He doesn‚Äôt give someone everything nor take everything from someone.‚Äù Hawking is given a brilliant mind and many compassionate people around him throughout his life. On the other hand, his simplest abilities for living are taken away from him. To achieve whatever goals of your life, you need to appreciate and utilize what you are given, not what you wish you had. Hawking realized that, he seized that, and he became who he is now. Remember: no one has everything or lose everything; just look around you more carefully, you will find things or reasons to keep you up.¬†  Strongly recommend this film to anybody. Eddie Redmayne did a very good job playing Stephen Hawking. No wonder he got the Oscars Award for Best Actor in 2014.¬†

text: I respect Stephen Hawkings and his contribution to science, but don't appreciate him bashing about religion. It's okay if you don't believe in God, and remember, most of the greatest of scientists and mathematicians like Albert Einstein and Darwin(before he died, he did not want his followers to produce his manuscripts because he claimed it was all a lie.) did believe in God. So to ridicule people who believe in something is just ridiculous. People ask me, how do you there is a god? Well, because I was desperate and I searched for God with all my heart and with everything I had, and I found him. I found him with faith, see, without faith you cannot see God. Faith is a SUBSTANCE of things hoped for, faith is also a revelation. In the Christian world, you cannot know God if you don't have faith. That's because, God has to REVEAL or UNVEIL himself to you for you to know that He is real. And no, God does not have to come in human form to you. When He reveals himself to you, it will be so simple that you might even miss it if you were not paying attention. He can come as a thought, a sign, a dream, or even come down from heaven himself so you can see, depending on the size of you FAITH in him, if you have so much¬†faith in Him, he won't have to come in¬†his fullness, He will just reveal himself¬†to you in¬†a thought that will trouble you for even years.¬†But God will never ever show himself to anyone who just halfheartedly is looking for him. NEVER, you can scream God never exists, but if you have never searched Him the way you search for science to find all your answers, you will never be real, and you will never acquire faith to believe in Him. After all, the whole Christian way of living is with faith, because without faith, you cannot go to heaven, you cannot believe God, you cannot please God, and simply, you cannot be saved and forgiven. text: This looks like a very very dull film and Austin Powers did spring to mind for me. Just because it is filled with courage, genius, adversity, tragedy and no doubt good acting, isn't going to make it interesting. This film would never have been made without the fact that the main character happens to suffer from a progressive disease. It is in that respect an exploitation movie. Hawking and his wife may not in fact be very interesting people and aside from his disease and popularist publications, nobody would really be aware of Hawking. People with far greater reputations than Hawking and with much more varied and interesting private lives than he, such as Einstein, Halley, Newton, Galileo, Tesla, Edison, Oppenheimer or Feynman would have been better candidates. Sadly these films would have been about personalities and ideas rather than a domestic situation. Hawking isn't even a Nobel Prize winner and never invented anything. It's annoying when people get all excited about that-there science. People with an education quickly switch Brian Cox off for being deeply patronising by not only dumbing-down but presuming that other people know absolutely nothing. He even repeated the myth about Newton and the Apple, a myth, but happy to take the money for it. The very idea of somebody being a professor in their 40s twenty years ago would have been laughable, because they simply would have not published enough to make that grade. There are lots of perfectly good documentaries about Hawking around, but they don't make money or win Oscars the way a film aimed at people who need to go to the cinema to feel emotions safely separated from their own lives do.

After 2 hours during which I did my best not to cry I could not help but think of the beautiful but devastating impact the film must have had on him and his carer to watch it.  This is a brilliant and sensitive film, moreover one based on a true story. Though I did not cry, as if I had let one tear roll down my cheek it would have been immediately followed by hundreds more.

Would you kick someone's ass because they fooled you? Would you do something that you wouldn't do now because of your religion?  Try to elaborate it.Brainstorm on it. text: Do not get me wrong Stephen Hawking has accomplished a lot of amazing things in his life (he's very brilliant) but watching this trailer makes me sad. Today due to the progression of the disease Stephen cannot even push himself in a wheelchair or talk more than a word a minute (due to lack of control in his hands). Also not only did his first marriage fail but his second one too. And to top it all off the poor man has difficulties breathing requiring a ventilator at all times. I complain about my own trials but I could never overcome the problems Stephen has if I were in his situation. I hate what he has and still goes through but my gosh is he my hero. He may not be a perfect man but he is a fighter!

text: Hawking is the perfect symbol for what science is today: crippled & speaking with an  artificial, mechanical voice.  He's the figure of trans-humanism made real which serves to underscore the entire fantasy of black holes of every size & type imaginable;  big bang expanding universes resulting from unobserved dark energy & dark matter; and, gravity waves claimed to be observed millions of light years away but never on the earth itself despite billions of dollars spent on LIGO experiments that have detected absolutely nothing.  Never mind that the mathematics behind the three types of big bang universes contradicts the four types of black hole universes which never match any of the big bang universes & contradict each other no matter the combination.  On Youtube, see mathematician Steven Crothers at the Electric Universe conference destroy the mathematical inconsistencies & bogus assumptions (e.g. dividing by zero as an expression of infinity) of Hawking, Penrose, & Einstein, as well as, Dr. P. M. Robitaille's nullification of Kirchoff's Law on which the Planck constant is derived &, in turn,  on which Einstein's relatvity is derived, thus nullifying the claims of both Planck & Einstein.  Also, Robitaille shows how the so called background radiation of the big bang is nothing more than microwave radiation emitted from the oceans of the Earth.

text: The theory of everything is the sun: the sun heats and heats up and by the action of sending out heat,it produces its own nucleus and builds pressure inside of it. And when the sun heats,it releases pressure from the nucleus to the shell/covering. These steps are called 'pulse of heat' (beating of heat emanating from the sun). Our hearts make pulses of heat; engines make pulses of heat; lamps make pulses of heat; batteries make pulses of heat. Everything that consumes energy,sends out pulses of heat! This is also the reason why you see the nucleus and rings that the sun pruduces everywhere in nature. For example, when you throw a stone into a body of water, at the place where the stone lands, we see the shape of a nucleus and the rings emanating outward from the nucleus. The form of all living things is also a core(heart) And a circle(covering/skin). The shape of a plant also contains a nucleus(of the plant seed) and an encircling(shell of the fruit or stem leaves of the flower. By jeka

text: Stephen Hawking The interesting fact is that Stephen Hawking was born 8th January 1942 and I was born 8th January 1996, so Stephen Hawking is 54 years older than me. The date of his birth is also a 300th anniversary of the death of Galileo Galilei. Imagine how incredible he is. And Stephen Hawking has even the similar favourite topics as myself. Universe. Time, Space. Time-Space. Science. Technology... Of course when he is a scientist. And because he is not only a theoretical physicist, but also an author I consider him to be a polymath. I know that Stephen Hawking once said ,,People who boast about their IQs are stupid." But I doubt that Stephen Hawking has IQ 160. Stephen Hawking has IQ from 160-180. And IQ 180 he should have only because his own uniqueness, exceptionality and remarkability. I wish Stephen Hawking an infinity, eternity of time, space, knowledge, love, joy, life, humour, stoicism, optimism, wisdom, peace, fame, glory... I would like to see him in 2042, when he will be 100 years old. I do believe he will achieve it.

text: Takes a lot to get me to cry in a movie, so congrats on that one.     This man had everything. Intelligence, a beautiful partner, a body, opportunity, a future. He lost everything. Love can only go so far until it damages the individual's mental and emotional health. Although he kept his intelligence, fame and money, his capacity for emotional relationships was severely limited.  I think we can all take something from this. This man was a wonderful man, who had everything taken away from him, just like that.  Cherish the people in, have been, and will be in your life with all your heart. Live for them. Live for their happiness.     Live for them    .

text: Sorry i dont want to waste anyone's time but I just need to share my story.  Sometimes when I'm at school I like to separate myself from the rest of my class. Not by walking away but just by stop listening to the sounds around me and stop looking at the things around me. Normaly I look outside to the trees, the birds and the big , undiscovered sky above me.. but I didn't look at it two days ago. Two days ago I looked at a big poster on the wall for half an hour without looking away; 'The Theory of Everything' it said. I knew it was a movie before. But that day, two days ago I couldn't get my eyes of the poster. I looked Into eddies eyes, wandering away in my own thoughts. A few hours later, after dinner, I had to study for my math exam but I just couldn't stay focussed. My mind was with the poster and I felt like I had to watch it before continuing with my normal life. That night I couldn't sleep so I opened my window. I looked up and I had never seen a sky like that before. I saw more stars than ever before and they shined brighter than ever before. I started thinking: 'what is everything?' At that moment I opened my laptop and I put on this movie. I'll be honest with you all. I was very very touched. I laughed but I also had tears in my eyes because I was sad. Especially when I saw the scene where Jane said that she had loved Stephen, and Stephen started crying, I felt so bad. At that moment my phone vibrated, of course I didn't take a look at it because I was so focussed on the movie. But at the end, when I had just seen his life backwards. And the beautiful credit music started, I looked out my window again with the tears still in my eyes. Than I grabbed my phone and I saw this one pop up in my screen. 'Stephen Hawking passed away'.   I was shocked. I was angry but. I was crying like a little baby. I changed. I wanted to go and live my life to it's fullest potential. I wanted to Discover the universe, and find the meaning of it all. Please, if you are still reading. Noting and noone can stop you from being the person that you want to be. Please, don't try to be popular and don't be afraid to be yourself. You can only find answers about life if you live how you want to live. Thanks, good luck. And rest in Peace Stephen ‚ù§

text: When I was on my own world of Art, I started to think about movies I could watch. I stumble upon this movie. 'The Theory Of Everything'. I thought, cool, I can watch watch this for like all day. So, I put down my pencil and my sketch pad, mainly focus on the device, and watch it. I realized, it was the life of Stephen Hawking! Cool! I nver knew that he had this kind of life. Sad, happy, etc. He inspired me to love Science even more because at my 1st year of High School, one of my weaknesses is Science, along with Math. I then started to research about his life and his studies. I watched the movie over, and over, and over again. I even followed Eddie's other films like Fantastic Beast and Where To Find Them, etc. It was so spectacular to make a movie just like that. A week before my final exam in 1st year High School, I studied and studied and studied. Of course especially at Science. In my head was like, 'Yes, Science! I learned everything for me! Thanks, Mr. Hawking! ' I also watched the movie, even tge behind the scenes. But the day after, as I was browsing the best side of YouTube, this videi showed up. 'The Final Words Of Stephen Hawking'. I was like, what? That couldn't be happening,right? I click on the video. It was said he dued on March 14th of 2018 (or something), tge exact day I studied for Science. I feel all of the things that are heavy weigh me down like an ant being weighed down by a huge rock. No. This can't be happening. How?! I feel like I loss so much power and life. On the day of the exam at Science, I couldn't forget what I've heard. But most importantly I can't forget what have he done to the society. He helped people who have difficulties ib understanding about space and time. I still can't believe that he is dead now. In fact, Stephen died like a hero.  R. I. P.  Stephen Hawking. We love you all.
author: Chris Maddy

text: Beautiful story, beautiful movieüå∏ I have a story to share with you.   For a long time I had planned to see this movie, (mostly because Eddie Redmayne is my favorite actor since 2012 when I saw him in Les Miserables) but it never happened ,you know what I mean? This year I finally decided to watch it,  and I loved it! It was like I got to know Stephen, sure I had heard of him before, but I suddenly learned so much more. I was completely blown away by this story, and the music was something extremely powerful that I always cried to, and I couldn‚Äôt stop listen to it. About 2 days later the news were everywhere, and it for real broke my heart. Stephen is no longer with us, but I think he‚Äôs sitting up there somewhere, still exploring the universeüí´‚ú® He was a brilliant man, he knew what he was doing and had a head that is too unbelievable to understand. I feel kind of cursed because of this, how can he pass away 2 days later, just when I got to know him??... text: I remember the day, I was at biology class on 15th march morning, a friend opened Google for an answer, everybody was cheerful, after watching the news in trending, his first reaction was to me: WTF brother, Hawking is no more!! He knew that I was a fan of Hawking. I rememember the class went freeze at the moment, my mouth was opened and my eyeballs were stonified for some second... Though suddenly I thought it was fake or a joke but returning home I confirmed it... Time gone too fast, it has been more than one year since that day. But here, positively, at this very moment, I can't hold my eardrops even today while writing this comment ... He could have show us many new ways if he lived more, why god didn't took the lifespan of useless and harmful persons and gave that to him?

text: A man with absolutely no boundaries !! There's no one in history who's like him, No One !! He have seen the eternity of the macrocosm while being almost 100% paralyzed sitting on a wheel chair. We talk alot about Newton and Einstein's brilliance but most of humanity doesn't realize how astronomically brilliant Sir Stephen Hawking was, that man had nothing but only the cognitive part of his brain and that was more than enough for him. We humans always complain about how much of a hell our life is, we've always got something to complain about, we make excuses, blame others, tear each other down, never appreciate what we have, always taking things for granted. We should atleast try to be better than this after witnessing Sir Stephen Hawking's life. He did his works while being humorous all the time, always. That proves how much of a joyful person he was. We should really be grateful that we belong to the same era as his.

text: Then the evolution of life in the universe is not to achieve an inorganic life that's mostly machine, but rather a biological life so complex only a "quantum" computer could compare to this organism's brain that has achieved this feat of genetics. This theory in that the evolution of the human genome can continue to evolve based on it's ability to write a broader range of other microorganisms into it. These successful additions providing immunity. Similar to the twins. It's possible to also use this theory to explain how the dinosaurs evolved from the great lizards they once were to the feathered creatures they are now. Through the addition of microorganisms into their genome that provided a way to survive the changing atmospheres. Not just through digestion, but also the process of respiration down to the cellular level. Our goal then, as advanced humans would be to determine which organisms we are capable of using and which will prevent us from traveling to other planets.
